post_text:
Dear CJUSD Parents,
Last Wednesday, you or your student picked up a yellow envelope containing the 2020-21 back to school packet. In that envelope were two items requiring parent signatures: the Acknowledgement of Parent Annual Rights Notification, and the Student Acceptable Use Agreement and Release of District Liability Form. There was also a packet from food services that may be applicable to your family. Please sign and return those pages to your school's office (for CES: through the mail slot in the front door / for CJSHS: in the box outside the front door) by next Tuesday, September 1.
Thank you!

post_text:
Hello Wildcat Families,
Yesterday, July 27, Superintendent Smith-Hagberg sent out a letter to families outlining details regarding the upcoming school year (which is also posted on our website under the Updates on COVID-19 tab). The letter was followed by a message from each school's principal, requesting each family's instructional model selection be completed through a Google form. If you did not receive this message and have not selected your child(ren)'s preferred instructional model for the 2020-21 school year, please contact your school site.
Stay safe and be well!

Hello Calistoga Community,

The CJUSD Board of Trustees will be holding a special board meeting tomorrow, July 24, 2020 at 3:45 p.m. via Zoom to discuss the 2020-21 school reopening plans. To view the agenda and login information, please visit our BoardDocs website at: https://go.boarddocs.com/ca/cjusd/Board.nsf/vpublic?open

If you'd like to make a public comment, please submit a Google form by 11:00 a.m. tomorrow, and your statement will be read by a member of the Board. The Google form can be found here: https://www.calistogaschools.org/board_of_education/virtual_board_of_education_meetings

post_text:
Ms. Swarner’s Biotech students job shadowed today at Gritstone Oncology. They had an incredible experience learning about the history of immunotherapy and how the Gritstone team is passionate about seeking treatments that use a patient’s own immune system to fight off cancer. The adventuresome students also got to work on their aseptic technique. It’s harder than you may think! Don’t let those coveralls touch anything!

#IfTheyCanSeeItTheyCanBeIt #JobShadow #ReachHigher #DreamBig

NAPAVALLEYREGISTER.COM
Napa students mix with robots at Career Day

NapaLearns
February 14 at 6:31 PM ·

On February 12, 80 high school juniors and seniors interested in exploring a career in health care, computer science or robotic technology attended a Robotics Career Day at Queen of the Valley Medical Center.

Students from all 8 Napa County high schools, including Napa County Office of Education, Napa Valley Unified School District, St. Helena High School, Calistoga Junior-Senior High and Justin Sienna Catholic College Preparatory had hands-on experience with the latest robotics technology available. They also had the chance to learn firsthand from surgical team members who use these robots to perform less invasive surgeries.

It was an amazing day and thanks to everyone who participated!

Exciting basketball tonight at Calistoga HS!

SENIOR RECOGNITION NIGHT

The Wildcat girls play Roseland Collegiate at 6:00 to keep their undefeated league streak alive. This is the first ever girls basketball league championship team. The team is 20-2 this season!

The boys team needs a win at 7:30 to clinch the NCL 4 championship. A win tonight will be the first boys basketball league title since 1992.

Come out and support our teams and buy dinner at the snack bar to support Calistoga high school leadership class.

After beating Concord HS (1700+ students) and Tennyson (1300+ students), the Wildcats will take on the neighboring Maria Carrillo Pumas (1500+ students) for the CHAMPIONSHIP!!!

With only 250 students at CHS our undefeated 10-0 team looks to slay another giant.

I will post updates from the game for those who cannot attend.

GO WILDCATS!!!
